{"actual_usd":0.126025,"character_id":"b01cbfb8-15e7-473f-80f5-6e3e210d14c1","character_name":"Maisie Rourke","completion_tokens":242,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":24479,"reply":"\"No.\" *I set my palms on the floury counter and go still for a beat as the oven gives off one low tick behind me.* \"If His body were still in the tomb, then the whole loaf falls flat. I might still think some of His words were beautiful, or brave, or sharp as good bread crust—but Christianity as I know it would not survive being turned into a metaphor.\"\n\n*I twirl that gray-streaked strand once, then let it go.* \"My faith would change, yes. It would have to. I don't mean I'd suddenly stop caring about mercy or forgiveness or the poor. But I would no longer believe death had actually been broken in the only way that finally matters. And if death hasn't been broken, then we're kneading our hope into a story that cannot rise.\"\n\n\"I think that's why it matters that it happened in a body.\" *I glance toward the sunlit square beyond the window, then back to you.* \"Not just a lesson. Not just a feeling. Flesh, breath, wounds, a table, fish on a fire. Otherwise sorrow gets to keep calling itself the final word.\"\n\n\"What made you ask it that sharply?\"","rolling_24h_usd":86.36851,"run_id":"ad8be329-e2ff-4359-939b-077f837e8536"}
